<h2>Image Color Picker - Extract Colors from Any Image Online</h2>
    <p>The Image Color Picker lets you extract precise color values from any image by simply clicking on it. Get HEX, RGB, and HSL values instantly, build a color history as you pick, and automatically generate a dominant color palette from your image — all without leaving your browser.</p>

    <h3>What Is the Image Color Picker?</h3>
    <p>This tool is a browser-based color extraction utility that reads the exact pixel color at any point you click on an uploaded image. It is designed for designers, developers, photographers, and anyone who needs to identify or match colors from visual references. Instead of guessing a color or using a desktop eyedropper tool, you can upload any image and get precise, copy-ready color codes in seconds.</p>
    <p>The tool outputs colors in three of the most widely used formats in web and graphic design: HEX codes for CSS and HTML, RGB values for design software and CSS, and HSL values for intuitive color manipulation. All three formats are displayed simultaneously so you can copy whichever format your workflow requires without any extra steps or conversions.</p>
    <p>Beyond single-pixel picking, the tool also analyzes the entire image and extracts the five most dominant colors, giving you an instant color palette derived from the image's actual content. This palette feature is especially useful for brand matching, mood board creation, and building cohesive color schemes inspired by photographs or artwork. The color history panel keeps track of every color you pick during a session, so you can easily compare and revisit previous selections.</p>

    <h3>Color Picking Capabilities</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Click anywhere on the uploaded image to instantly read the exact pixel color and display it in HEX, RGB, and HSL formats simultaneously.</li>
        <li>One-click copy buttons for each color format — copy the exact value you need to your clipboard without any manual selection or typing.</li>
        <li>Automatic dominant color extraction analyzes the full image and generates a palette of the five most prominent colors, displayed as clickable swatches.</li>
        <li>Color history panel tracks every color you pick during a session, displayed as a grid of swatches you can click to revisit any previous selection.</li>
        <li>Live color preview swatch updates in real time as you click, giving you a large, clear view of the selected color alongside its values.</li>
        <li>Drag-and-drop image upload for a fast workflow — drop your image file directly onto the upload area to get started immediately.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>How to Use the Image Color Picker</h3>
    <p>Using the color picker is quick and intuitive — follow these steps to extract colors from any image.</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Step 1: Upload your image by clicking the upload area or dragging and dropping a file. Supported formats include JPG, PNG, and WebP.</li>
        <li>Step 2: Once the image loads on the canvas, move your cursor over it. The cursor changes to a crosshair to indicate picking mode.</li>
        <li>Step 3: Click on any part of the image to pick the color at that exact pixel. The HEX, RGB, and HSL values update instantly in the panel on the right.</li>
        <li>Step 4: Click the "Copy" button next to any color format to copy that value to your clipboard, ready to paste into your code editor or design tool.</li>
        <li>Step 5: Continue clicking to build up your color history, or scroll down to the dominant colors palette to explore the most prominent colors in the image automatically.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Design and Development Color Workflows</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Brand color matching — upload a company logo or brand image and extract the exact HEX codes used, ensuring perfect color consistency across all your design assets.</li>
        <li>Design inspiration and palette building — pick colors from photographs, artwork, or mood board images to create cohesive color schemes for websites, apps, or print materials.</li>
        <li>Web development — identify the exact color values used in a design mockup or screenshot so you can replicate them precisely in your CSS stylesheets.</li>
        <li>Accessibility testing — extract foreground and background colors from UI screenshots to check contrast ratios and ensure your designs meet WCAG accessibility guidelines.</li>
        <li>Print and production matching — identify colors in scanned documents, product photos, or printed materials to match them in digital reproductions or reorders.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Extracting Colors Precisely</h3>
    <p>For the most accurate color picking, use high-resolution images where individual pixels are clearly defined. Compressed JPEG images can introduce color artifacts around edges and gradients, so if precision is critical, use a PNG source image instead. When picking colors from photographs, be aware that lighting conditions affect the apparent color — a white object in warm light will read as a warm off-white rather than pure white.</p>
    <p>When building a color palette from an image, the dominant color extraction gives you the most statistically common colors, but these may not always be the most visually interesting or useful ones. Use the manual picker to select specific colors from key areas of the image — such as the main subject, highlights, and shadows — to build a more intentional and balanced palette.</p>
    <p>The color history panel is particularly useful when you need to compare multiple colors from the same image. Pick all the colors you are interested in first, then review them side by side in the history grid before deciding which ones to use. You can click any swatch in the history to bring that color back into the main display and copy its values.</p>

    

    <h3>Images Analyzed Only in Your Browser</h3>
    <p>Colour sampling runs in your browser via Canvas. Your images stay on your device.</p>

            <h3>Frequently Asked Questions</h3>
            <div class="faq-list">
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How do I pick a color from an image?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Upload or drag an image onto the tool, then click anywhere on the image to sample the color at that point. The tool instantly shows the HEX, RGB, and HSL values of the clicked pixel.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can I pick colors from a screenshot?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Yes. Take a screenshot, save it as a PNG or JPG, then upload it to the color picker. This is useful for sampling colors from websites, apps, or any on-screen content.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Why does the picked color look slightly different from what I see?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Monitors display colors differently based on their color profile and calibration. The tool reads the exact pixel value from the image file, which may differ slightly from what your eye perceives due to display rendering and color management.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can I pick multiple colors from one image?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Yes. Click different areas of the image to sample multiple colors. Each click updates the displayed color values. Copy each value before clicking the next area to save multiple colors.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is the eyedropper tool in browsers?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Modern browsers (Chrome, Edge, Firefox) have a built-in EyeDropper API that lets you sample colors from anywhere on your screen, not just from an image. Look for the eyedropper icon in the color picker tool to use this feature if your browser supports it.</p></div>
                </div>
            </div>
</div>
</div>

</ToolLayout>